We’ve all been there. You’re working on a massive monorepo, you trigger a build or run a type-check, and then… you wait. It’s the ultimate excuse to go grab a coffee while your CI pipeline spins.
Well, you might need a new excuse.
Microsoft just announced TypeScript 7.0, and it’s not just your usual minor update with a few new utility types. This is a massive generational leap. The biggest plot twist? TypeScript has been completely ported to native Go.
Let’s talk about why this matters, look at some wild performance benchmarks, and see how you can start using it today.
1. Wait, Why Go?
Since day one, TypeScript has been written in TypeScript. It’s a cool flex, but running a compiler on top of Node.js comes with some serious limits — especially when it comes to raw speed and multithreading.
To break past these limits, the TS team spent the last year rebuilding the compiler in Go. They kept the exact same logic so it’s 100% compatible with your existing code, but now it compiles down to native machine code. That means real parallel processing and way better memory management.
The TL;DR? It’s up to 10x faster.
When they tested this on massive open-source projects, the numbers were honestly ridiculous:
It’s not just build times, either. It uses about 6% to 26% less RAM.
If you use VS Code, you’ll feel this immediately. In the VS Code repo itself, the time it takes to see that first red error squiggle after opening a file went from 17.5 seconds down to just 1.3 seconds.
2. You’re in Control: The New Worker Flags
Because TS 7.0 is native, it handles parsing and type-checking in parallel automatically. But since type-checking can get messy with file dependencies, they gave us some cool new flags to control how much hardware we throw at it:

• --checkers: This sets the number of worker threads. It defaults to 4. Got a beefy machine with 16 cores? Crank this up and watch your build fly.

• --singleThreaded: Turns off parallelization completely. This is super handy if you’re debugging or running builds on a cheap, low-spec CI runner.
How it looks in your terminal:
# Throw 8 workers at a massive project
npx tsc --checkers 8# Play it safe on a low-end CI runner
npx tsc --singleThreaded
3. Emojis and Template Literals Finally Play Nice
Speed is great, but they also fixed some annoying bugs in the type system. If you’ve ever done crazy string manipulations with Template Literal Types, you might have noticed it sometimes mangled complex Unicode characters (like emojis).
TS 7.0 fixes this completely. Your string types are now totally safe.
Quick Example:
// TS 7.0 now perfectly handles Unicode at the type level
type WelcomeMessage<T extends string> = `👋 Hello, ${T}!`;type User = "Developer 🚀";
// Evaluates exactly to: "👋 Hello, Developer 🚀!"
type Greeting = WelcomeMessage<User>;
function sendGreeting(msg: Greeting) {
console.log(msg);
}
// ✅ Totally fine
sendGreeting("👋 Hello, Developer 🚀!");
// ❌ Error! TS 7.0 catches that the rocket emoji is missing
sendGreeting("👋 Hello, Developer !");
4. The Catch: How to Migrate
Okay, there is one catch. TypeScript 7.0 doesn’t have a public programmatic API yet (they’re saving that for 7.1).
Why does this matter? Tools like typescript-eslint rely on that API to work. If you upgrade blindly, your linter might break.
But don’t panic! You can run TS 7.0 and 6.0 side-by-side using NPM aliases in your package.json:
{
"devDependencies": {
"@typescript/native": "npm:typescript@^7.0.0",
"typescript": "npm:@typescript/typescript6@^6.0.0"
}
}With this setup, when you run npx tsc, you get the blazing-fast Go compiler. But your linters and external tools will quietly use the TS 6.0 API under the hood. Best of both worlds!
Should You Upgrade?
100% yes. If you’re working on anything larger than a tiny side project, the time savings are massive. Slack engineers said this update cut their CI type-checking time from 7.5 minutes to a little over 1 minute. It’s an absolute no-brainer.
reference: https://devblogs.microsoft.com/typescript/announcing-typescript-7-0/
